{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ff1c2b23-0e72-4ed5-8071-515f67d16ef0","content":"The repository doesn't contain documentation on this topic, but I can answer from general .NET knowledge:\n\n**Recovering a macOS crash dump without `createdump`:**\n\n1. **Check Apple's crash reporter** — macOS automatically saves crash logs to:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   Look for `.ips` or `.crash` files matching your process name.\n\n2. **Enable core dumps** before running:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   sudo sysctl kern.corefile=/tmp/cores/core.%P\n   mkdir -p /tmp/cores\n   ```\n   After a crash, the core file appears at the configured path.\n\n3. **Use `lldb` to inspect the core**:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /tmp/cores/core.12345 /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n\n4. **If SIP blocks core dumps**, you may need to:\n   - Boot into Recovery Mode and run `csrutil enable --without debug`\n   - Or sign your binary with the `com.apple.security.get-task-allow` entitlement\n\n5. **For NativeAOT specifically**, since `createdump` isn't bundled, the native core dump from macOS is your primary option. You can analyze it with `lldb` and use the [dotnet-sos](https://learn.microsoft.com/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-sos) plugin (`plugin load libsosplugin.dylib`) for managed-aware debugging.\n\n**Key note:** NativeAOT crash dumps are essentially native core dumps — standard macOS/lldb workflows apply, unlike CoreCLR where `createdump` provides a richer managed dump.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bf1c4bf4-b2d6-48ce-ad72-a37a2444200f","outputTokens":425,"requestId":"AC0A:2E3AFD:13F18DE:166A99F:6A06720D"},"id":"021d0ac4-701a-4b56-b859-cef4fa91be67","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:08:40.730Z","parentId":"7220dc48-8999-4132-8bd0-56fb64023564"}
